Van Eyck became involved as a player and technician of village's carillon by 1619.
He met with several craftsmen and the city organist to discuss changes and improvements to the carillon, which he carried out in 1620 and 1621.
In 1623 and 1624, he was employed by the city of Utrecht to repair and renovate the Dom Tower's clock and carillon.
His title was changed to "Director of the Bell-Works" in 1628, and he was entrusted with the technical supervision of all the bells of the city.
In 1631, he had a small keyboard composed of 30 small bells constructed for instruction.

Jonkheer Jacob van Eyck ( van IKE, Dutch: [ˈjaː.kɔp vɑn ˈɛik]; c. 1590 – 26 March 1657) was a Dutch nobleman and blind musician.
Jacob van Eyck was born in 1589 or 1590 into a noble family probably in the small town of Heusden.
A year later, after negotiations with the city, he left home to become the city carillonneur.
Over the years, he undertook projects to expand and improve the bell towers at the city hall, the Nicolaaskerk, Sint Janskerk and the Jacobikerk.
A year later, he was appointed the carillonneur of Sint Janskerk.
One of these was Marin Mersenne, who was the first to codify the harmonics of a vibrating spring.

In 1633, Van Eyck told Isaac Beeckman that the ideal series of a bell's partials consisted of three notes each an octave apart, supplemented by a minor third and perfect fifth in the second octave, and he convinced Beeckman to write about it in his journal on 24 September.
Hemony carillons outfitted with "pure" tuned bells quickly became the standard and were coveted across Europe for decades.
The final years of Van Eyck's life were spent in declining health.
He was buried the next day, and for three hours, the bells of Sint Janskerk, the Jacobikerk, and the Dom Tower were tolled in his memory.
The Utrecht Bellringers Guild awards the Jacob van Eyck Prize every three years to fund the preservation of Dutch cultural and historical heritage and campanological research.
The themes include folk songs, dance tunes, church works, psalms, and songs of the day, as well as a few original compositions by Van Eyck.
Some of the best known include a variation on John Dowland's "Flow, my tears" and a favorite Christmas carol at the time, "Unto Us Is Born a Son".
